The obvious target is mopsus (long-lived daemon, spawns Codex constantly). I'll argue the opposite.

- **Mopsus is production.** Telegram daemon, two launchd jobs, real users, the tool-digest job that *staged this very debate*. Don't refactor the thing whose output you're acting on.
- **heated-debate is the right test bed:** one file (`shelley.ts`), per-round subprocess fan-out, trivially revertible, no users besides the user.
- **Dogfooding loop closes nicely:** heated-debate is the tool Mopsus invokes to evaluate new tools. Making it the *first* adopter is the cleanest feedback channel — Mopsus's next tool digest will run *through* the upgraded engine and surface remote-control's wins/losses in the next debate.
- **Cold-start math:** a 5-round debate spawns ~10 `codex exec` processes. A persistent app-server collapses that to 2 (one per agent), preserved across rounds. Round latency is currently the bottleneck — Mopsus times out heated-debate at 1200s for a reason.

